Claims WHAT IS CLAIMED IS: 1. A method for authenticating a user, comprising: (a) presenting, via an electronic device, a geographic map based on a multi factor authentication (MFA) process associated with an account; (b) receiving, from the electronic device, an authentication attempt, the authentication attempt including a geographic indicator identifying a geographic location on the geographic map selected by the user, and interaction information describing user interactions with the geographic map when selecting the geographic location; (c) based at least in part on the interaction information, determining whether the geographic location was selected by a human or a computer attempting to impersonate the human; (d) determining whether the geographic indicator matches information identifying the user as part of the multi-factor authentication process; and (e) sending, to the electronic device, an authentication result indicating whether the geographic location was determined to be selected by the human in the determining in step (c) and the geographic indicator was determined to match information identifying the user in step (d). 2. The method of claim 1, wherein the interaction information includes a first path from a starting location on the geographic map to the geographic location, and the determining (c) comprises: determining a second path associated with a successful authentication corresponding to the geographic location; and comparing the first path to the second path. 3. The method of claim 1, wherein the geographic indicator includes response coordinates, and the determining (d) comprises: determining expected coordinates associated with the geographic location; determining a zoom level associated with a graphical user interface displaying the geographic map; determining a threshold value based on the zoom level; and 

 determining whether a difference between the response coordinates and the expected coordinates is less than the threshold value. 4. The method of claim 1, further comprising: determining the geographic location based on a communication received from an electronic device associated with the account; and requesting identification of the geographic location within the geographic map based on the determining and the MFA process. 5. The method of claim 1, further comprising: identifying a financial transaction associated with the account; determining the geographic location based on the financial transaction; and requesting identification of the geographic location within the geographic map based on the determining and the MFA process. 6. The method of claim 1, further comprising: receiving an identifier of the geographic location during an administration process associated with the account; assigning the geographic location to the account; and requesting identification of the geographic location within the geographic map based on the assigning and the MFA process. 7. The method of claim 1, wherein the determining (c) comprises: determining a pattern based on a history of authentication attempts; and comparing the authentication attempt to the pattern. 8. The method of claim 1, wherein the selection information includes at least one of a swipe action, a zoom action, a drag action, a scroll action, or a pin drop action within a graphical user interface displaying the geographic map. 9. The method of claim 1, wherein presenting the geographic map comprises: determining an anti-phishing location associated with the account; and 

 initializing the geographic map with a starting point corresponding to the anti phishing location. 10. A non-transitory computer-readable device having instructions stored thereon that, when executed by at least one computing device, cause the at least one computing device to perform operations comprising: (a) presenting, via an electronic device, a geographic map based on a multi factor authentication (MFA) process associated with an account; (b) receiving, from the electronic device, an authentication attempt, the authentication attempt including a geographic indicator identifying a geographic location on the geographic selected by a user, and interaction information describing user interactions with the geographic map when selecting the geographic location; (c) based at least in part on the interaction information, determining whether the geographic location was selected by a human or a computer attempting to impersonate the human; (d) determining whether the geographic indicator matches information identifying the user as part of the multi-factor authentication process; and (e) sending, to the electronic device, an authentication result indicating whether the geographic location was determined to be selected by the human in the determining in step (c) and the geographic indicator was determined to match information identifying the user in step (d). 11. The non-transitory computer-readable device of claim 10, the operations further comprising: identifying a financial transaction associated with the account; determining the geographic location based on the financial transaction; and requesting identification of the geographic location within the geographic map based on the MFA process. 12. The non-transitory computer-readable device of claim 10, the operations further comprising: receiving an identifier of the geographic location during an administration process associated with the account; 

 assigning the geographic location to the account; and requesting identification of the geographic location within the geographic map based on the assigning and the MFA process. 13. The non-transitory computer-readable device of claim 10, wherein the interaction information includes a first path from a starting location on the geographic map to the geographic location, and the (c) comprises: determining a second path associated with a successful authentication corresponding to the geographic location; and comparing the first path to the second path. 14. The non-transitory computer-readable device of claim 10, wherein the determining (c) comprises: determining a pattern based on a history of authentication attempts; comparing the authentication attempt to the pattern. 15. A system comprising: a memory; a communication interface; and one or more processor and/or circuits coupled to the memory and configured to: (a) present a geographic map based on a multi-factor authentication (MFA) process associated with an account; (b) receive, via the communication interface, an authentication attempt, the authentication attempt including a geographic indicator identifying a geographic location on the geographic map selected by a user, and interaction information describing user interactions with the geographic map when selecting the geographic location; (c) determine whether the geographic location was selected by a human or a computer attempting to impersonate the human based at least in part on the interaction information; (d) determine whether the geographic indicator matches information identifying the user as part of the multi-factor authentication process; and 

 (e) send, via the communication interface, an authentication result indicating whether geographic location was determined to be selected by the human in the determining in step (c) and the geographic indicator was determined to match information identifying the user in step (d). 16. The system of claim 15, wherein the one or more processors and/or circuits are further configured to: identify a financial transaction associated with the account; determine the geographic location based on the financial transaction; and request identification of the geographic location within the geographic map based on the determining and the MFA process. 17. The system of claim 15, wherein the one or more processors and/or circuits are further configured to: receive an identifier of the geographic location during an administration process associated with the account; assign the geographic location to the account; and request identification of the geographic location within the geographic map based on the assigning and the MFA process. 18. The system of claim 15, wherein the interaction information includes a first path from a starting location on the geographic map to the geographic location, and to determine in step (c), the one or more processors and/or circuits are further configured to: determine a second path associated with a successful authentication corresponding to the geographic location; and compare the first path to the second path. 19. The system of claim 15, wherein the geographic indicator includes response coordinates, and to determine in step (d), the one or more processors and/or circuits are further configured to: determine expected coordinates associated with the geographic location; determine a zoom level associated with a graphical user interface displaying the geographic map; 

 determine a threshold value based on the zoom level; and determine whether a difference between the response coordinates and the expected coordinates is less than the threshold value. 20. The system of claim 15, wherein to present in step (a), the one or more processors and/or circuits are further configured to: determine an anti-phishing location associated with the account; and initialize the geographic map with a starting point corresponding to the anti phishing location.
